"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多内容请参阅《隆隆座椅》</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/thank-tesla-the-biggest-obstacle-to-ev-ownership-will-soon-be-history-dc9945be?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">感谢特斯拉：拥有电动汽车的最大障碍很快就会成为历史</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2024-rolls-royce-spectre-review-electrified-at-last-45414642?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2024 款劳斯莱斯 Spectre：终于电气化</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2024-dodge-hornet-r-t-review-an-italian-stallion-made-for-america-ecd3ff48?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2024 道奇大黄蜂 R/T：意大利种马，为美国制造</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-range-rover-phev-review-a-hybrid-worth-plugging-in-1a4d7990?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2023 Range Rover PHEV：值得插入的混合动力车</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-maserati-grecale-modena-review-dont-call-it-a-comeback-yet-20f83ef0?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2023 玛莎拉蒂 Grecale Modena：还不算卷土重来</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-porsche-911-carrera-t-review-last-manual-stand-7df1e7e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2023-porsche-911-carrera-t-review-last-manual-stand-7df1e7e8<author><![CDATA[Dan Neil]]></author><category>下班</category><category>机动车</category><category>乘用车</category><category>汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>保时捷汽车控股有限公司。</category><category> PAH3.XE</category><category> XE:PAH3</category><category>保时捷</category><category>汽车</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>机动车</category><category>乘用车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bank of Japan Hints It Will Accept Higher Rates, Lifting Bond Yields]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尽管日本央行行长上田表示货币宽松政策仍然存在，但分析师预计最终会加息<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092536"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825540?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">日本央行行长上田一夫表示，央行不会过早加息。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Dhiraj Singh/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092536"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/megumi-fujikawa" itemprop="url" rel="author">藤川惠</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 7:49（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>东京——<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/8301" class="">日本央行</a><span class="company-name-type">长达</span>十年的激进货币宽松政策已进入倒计时，尽管市场对于还剩下多少时间存在分歧。</p><p>日本央行周五让10年期日本国债收益率升至近九年高点，行长上田一夫表示，他将给予市场更多自由来推高收益率。</p><p>但上田表示，此举并不意味着央行放弃其前任黑田东彦<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-most-radical-experiment-in-monetary-policy-isnt-working-1488135495?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">十多年来推行的货币宽松政策</a>。黑田东彦的政策包括负短期利率和大量购买政府债券，以严格控制 10 年期债券收益率，最近为 0.5%。</p><p>该银行周五表示， <a href="https://www.boj.or.jp/en/mopo/mpmdeci/mpr_2023/k230728a.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">0.5%的上限现在只是一个建议</a>，而不是硬性限制，并将新的硬性限制设定为1%。不久之后，10年期日本国债收益率短暂触及0.575%，为2014年9月以来的最高水平，随后又回落至0.54%。</p><p>日本的利率变动对美国市场很重要，因为日本金融机构是美国政府和公司债券的主要投资者。日本利率上升可能会导致一些人试图将资金带回国内，从而影响美国债券市场并压低美元兑日元汇率。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="760" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825615?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>上田表示，新政策旨在“提高货币宽松框架的可持续性”。他表示，他认为不会达到新的 1% 界限，称其为“以防万一的上限”。</p><p>但他也将更大的灵活性描述为对冲风险，并表示如果<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-inflation-hits-four-decade-high-pressuring-central-bank-in-2023-11671791596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-needs-more-confidence-inflation-will-stay-high-to-change-policy-ueda-says-4b1b7a16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">持续</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-inflation-hits-four-decade-high-pressuring-central-bank-in-2023-11671791596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超出预期，</a>这可能会有所帮助。通胀率一直在3%以上，高于日本央行2%的目标，日本央行上调了本财年的通胀预期，承认其4月份的预测未能体现日本物价上涨的持久性。</p><p>市场人士表示，上田对利率上升的容忍以及央行对通胀风险的暗示表明，明年可能会采取进一步措施，例如结束负短期利率或取消债券收益率上限。</p><p>如果是这样，日本将迟来地追随<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美联储</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-july-83e574cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧洲央行</a>自去年以来所走过的道路，这两家银行都在稳步提高基准利率以对抗通胀。</p><p>摩根大通经济学家藤田绫子表示，她曾认为明年春天结束负利率的可能性较小，但现在认为明年春天发生负利率的“可能性大大增加”。</p><p>法国巴黎银行经济学家河野龙太郎表示，他认为该行周五宣布的更大灵活性是“为日本央行废除负利率时长期收益率面临上行压力做准备”。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-28-2023/card/what-could-higher-yields-in-japan-mean-for-global-markets--3Lo857fcscixR5wkuBKQ?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资者不太确定</a>如何看待这些举措。日本央行宣布消息后，日经股指在最初几分钟内大幅下跌，但随后收复大部分失地，收盘下跌 0.4%。</p><p>日元最初因利率上升的预期而上涨（这将使日元计价的资产更具吸引力），然后在日本央行行长上田的新闻发布会上出现波动，因为他暗示加息不会迫在眉睫。</p><p>银行股大幅上涨，因为较高的政府债券收益率意味着它们可以对商业贷款收取更高的利率，并从债券和其他投资中获得更高的收益。</p><p>汽车制造商等日本出口商过去一年普遍从日元疲软中获利，这使得他们从日本的出口产品以美元计算更具竞争力。三井住友DS资产管理公司策略师Masahiro Ichikawa表示，只要利率不大幅上涨，投资者就应该对企业利润感到放心。</p><p> “日本央行可能会阻止收益率快速上升，以表明其不会退出，”Ichikawa 表示。</p><p>在权衡日本央行对政府债券收益率的上限（这是全球央行中的非正统工具）时，一些分析师将其与日本央行的股票购买计划进行了比较，该计划已停止积极购买，但尚未正式取消。同样，他们表示，即使在技术上仍然存在，收益率上限实际上也可能会逐渐取消。</p><p> — <em>Kosaku Narioka 对本文做出了贡献。</em></p><p>写信给藤川惠<a href="mailto:megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 11:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b<author><![CDATA[Megumi Fujikawa]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行业务</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>货币政策</category><category>央行干预</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>债务/债券市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务/债券市场</category><category>国家政府债务/债券市场</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>日本银行</category><category>8301.TO</category><category>邮编：8301</category><category>上田一夫</category><category>货币政策</category><category>央行干预</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>债务</category><category>债券市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务</category><category>国家政府债务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hong Kong Loses Court Bid to Ban Protest Song Appearing on Google]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>法官拒绝发布阻止在线传播抗议国歌的命令，称犯罪行为可以受到该市现行法律的惩罚<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093014"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825457?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">此案加剧了香港科技公司面临的寒意。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路易丝·德尔莫特/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093014"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/newley-purnell" itemprop="url" rel="author">纽利·珀内尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 6:22（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-loses-court-bid-to-ban-protest-song-appearing-on-google-ef360d4b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——一名法官驳回了政府禁止在网上传播<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-faces-pressure-in-hong-kong-over-search-results-for-national-anthem-11670324818?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流行民主歌曲</a>的提议，这对香港将国家安全打压范围扩大到谷歌等在线平台的努力造成打击。</p><p>这项裁决是由政府领导人亲自挑选的该市国家安全案件法官之一做出的，这是该市法院对寻求消除异议的地方当局造成的一系列挫折中的最新一项。</p><p>如果法官同意下达这项旨在禁止在全球范围内发行歌曲《愿荣光归香港》的命令，这将使香港与谷歌和其他平台发生冲突。分析师表示，这样的禁令可能会导致这些公司及其服务退出这个金融中心，与中国不同，该金融中心几十年来一直享有基本开放的互联网。</p><p>此案加剧了香港科技公司面临的寒意，将网上异议的目标从个人转移到平台本身。近几个月来，出于对国家安全法的担忧，美国科技巨头一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-tech-giants-are-slowly-cutting-off-hong-kong-internet-users-bd50cd8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在一点点地将香港用户拒之门外</a>。</p><p>香港律政司上个月向香港高等法院申请禁令，禁止播放或分发这首歌，包括在互联网和任何可在线访问的媒体上播放或分发这首歌，自大规模集会以来，这首歌已被亲民主示威者采用为国歌。 2019年爆发了抗议活动。</p><p>该法律行动没有点名任何具体公司，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a> <span class="company-name-type">Inc. 旗下的</span>谷歌因这首歌卷入了一场争议，因为当局<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-twitter-google-face-free-speech-test-in-hong-kong-11593790205?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">采取行动，利用三年前中国在香港实施的国家安全法来压制异议。</a>民众骚乱的后果</p><p>政府向法院申请的命令包括谷歌 YouTube 上与这首歌相关的 32 个视频的链接。</p><p>谷歌发言人拒绝置评。该市司法部没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>自国家安全法实施以来，《愿荣光归香港》实际上已被当局取缔， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-police-arrest-harmonica-player-after-protest-tune-played-at-queen-funeral-vigil-11663675638" target="_blank" class="icon none">警方逮捕了在公共场所播放或在网上发布该游戏的人</a>。</p><p>法官 Anthony Chan 在裁决摘要中表示：“经过仔细考虑，法院认为该禁令不会真正发挥作用，因为这些行为属于犯罪行为，应受到强有力的刑事制度的惩罚。”</p><p>政府有权向上级法院对该决定提出上诉。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825573?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">香港当局一直以国家安全的名义镇压异见人士。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路易丝·德尔莫特/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>过去八个月，香港最高法院两次在与镇压异议相关的备受瞩目的案件中做出不利于政府的裁决。在一个案件中，它否认政府阻止报业大亨黎智英聘请外国律师为他辩护以应对国家安全指控的努力。政府后来要求中国政府修改法律，实际上推翻了这一决定。</p><p>在另一起案件中，终审法院推翻了一名记者的定罪，该记者因在查阅车辆记录以撰写关于该市警方对 2019 年暴徒袭击抗议者的反应的调查报告时做出虚假陈述。</p><p>香港司法机构在不受政治压力的情况下做出裁决的能力受到外国企业和外交官的密切关注，将其视为香港剩余自由的晴雨表。香港的政治反对派已被清除，亲北京的忠诚者现在占据了香港的立法机构。</p><p>国家安全法取消了对被指控犯有此类罪行的人的一些保护，使政府能够亲自挑选负责国家安全案件的法官，限制一个人接受陪审团审判的权利，并增加获得保释的难度。</p><p>香港官员和亲北京人士严厉批评谷歌在香港国歌搜索结果中突出显示这首抗议歌曲。</p><p>市政府官员表示，这首支持民主的歌曲的歌词包含相当于鼓吹分裂国家的口号。他们对一些全球体育赛事的组织者错误地播放这首歌作为香港国歌而不是中国的《义勇军进行曲》的一系列事件表示愤怒。</p><p>这首抗议歌曲在谷歌中的突出表现导致多项国际体育赛事的播放出现混乱，引发了香港警方有组织犯罪调查科的调查。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em><em>您认为谷歌未来在香港运营会变得更加困难吗？</em>加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>一名香港高级官员去年表示，政府正在与谷歌及其视频平台 YouTube 讨论搜索结果。</p><p>谷歌表示，其搜索结果是由算法决定的，而不是由人工管理决定的，当搜索查询与网页上的文本匹配时，可能会出现一些令人反感的结果。</p><p>香港官员表示，他们已经努力优化政府网站页面，以获得更准确的结果，“义勇军进行曲”的政府页面现在在香港国歌的谷歌搜索中占据显着位置。</p><p>与互联网受到严格控制的中国大陆不同，香港的网络访问长期以来基本上是开放的。外国公司经常将信息的自由流动作为其驻扎在金融中心的原因。</p><p>尽管如此，香港警方近年来还是逮捕了几名因在社交媒体上发布内容的公民。</p><p>美国科技公司通常遵守其运营所在国家/地区的当地法律，无论是新加坡、沙特阿拉伯还是美国，有时还会限制特定国家/地区的材料被访问。</p><p> 2020 年，谷歌、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta</a>和 Twitter 表示，在北京实施国家安全法后，他们将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whatsapp-to-suspend-processing-law-enforcement-requests-for-user-data-in-hong-kong-11594034580?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">停止处理香港索取用户数据的请求</a>，该法限制了这个前英国殖民地长期以来享有的言论自由权。</p><p>写信给纽利·珀内尔<a href="mailto:newley.purnell@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">newley.purnell@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 10:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-loses-court-bid-to-ban-protest-song-appearing-on-google-ef360d4b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-loses-court-bid-to-ban-protest-song-appearing-on-google-ef360d4b<author><![CDATA[Newley Purnell]]></author><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Great Power Rivalry Looms Over Ukraine Grain Deal]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>俄罗斯对乌克兰谷物的封锁可能导致与中国、土耳其的裂痕<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001090198"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824549?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">俄罗斯阻止乌克兰粮食出口的举动将导致全球粮食价格走高。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·克拉夫琴科/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001090198"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alistair-macdonald" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿利斯泰尔·麦克唐纳</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 6:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——俄罗斯决定<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-russia-killed-the-ukraine-grain-deal-faf1f8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出允许乌克兰粮食向全球出口的协议，</a>这是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>总统的一场高风险赌博，这可能会导致与俄罗斯两个最有影响力的伙伴中国和土耳其的外交紧张。</p><p>俄罗斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阻止乌克兰大量粮食出口的</a>举动将进一步削弱其对手的经济，并可能通过推高全球粮食价格来增加俄罗斯自身的粮食出口收入。但这也带来了巨大的代价，因为它给中国（该协议下乌克兰粮食的最大接收国）带来了经济压力，并导致与土耳其的关系紧张。土耳其是去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-ukraine-face-thorny-issues-to-complete-implement-grain-deal-11658408580?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">帮助促成俄罗斯和乌克兰之间最初协议的</a>另一个主要买家。</p><p>随着乌克兰战争的拖延，俄罗斯的举动是普京再次尝试对对手和伙伴采取外交强硬态度的一部分。除了退出协议外，俄罗斯还对乌克兰黑海港口和粮食出口基础设施<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发动了一波导弹袭击</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要攻击该水道上的民用船只</a>，加剧了该海域战略航道周围的紧张局势。英国国防部表示，俄罗斯本周将一艘军舰驶入黑海南部的航运走廊。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="710" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/c26938bc-3e77-4f72-bf42-84d67b50b249-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>据外交官和分析人士称，普京无视了土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安就重返该协议进行谈判的要求。外交官称，埃尔多安最近几周多次表示，他计划与普京通话以重启该协议，但迄今为止尚未进行电话通话。他们说，土耳其官员继续通过各种其他渠道向克里姆林宫施压这个问题。</p><p>试图续签协议的时间已经不多了。到9月份，乌克兰的粮食收成将开始堆积在储存中，这使得及时出口变得更加困难，并给埃尔多安和其他领导人带来压力，要求他们及时恢复协议。</p><p>黑海粮食倡议仍然是战争中为数不多的外交突破之一。根据该协议，乌克兰出口了超过3200万吨粮食，帮助降低了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-heat-waves-lead-food-inflation-will-follow-ee6a32c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界各地的粮食价格</a>，并缓解了人们对入侵造成的全球饥饿危机加剧的担忧。</p><p>俄罗斯退出粮食协议还将给埃及等国家带来压力。埃及是世界上最大的小麦进口国，也是美国的安全伙伴，尽管受到华盛顿的压力，埃及在战争期间仍与俄罗斯保持着友好关系。埃及正面临创纪录的 60% 食品通胀和快速贬值的货币，导致进口成本极高。自战争爆发以来，该国一直从印度和其他地方采购，大部分谷物是从俄罗斯和乌克兰进口的。</p><p>帮助斡旋和监督该协议的联合国以及美国、中国和其他国家都呼吁俄罗斯重返该协议。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2084" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/670c660e-e0c9-43e9-8c6d-a5cb03e5d9e4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “共同的因素是我们希望俄罗斯联邦重新采取主动行动。最近我们看到黑海局势升级，这非常令人担忧，”一位熟悉相关情况的西方外交官表示。</p><p>英国国防部在周三的最新情报中表示，粮食协议有助于保护黑海地区免于陷入冲突，但表示，由于俄罗斯撤出并部署了一艘小型军舰“谢尔盖·科托夫”号，风险正在上升。进入该地区。报告称：“该地区暴力的强度和范围目前有可能增加。”俄罗斯尚未对这艘船的重新定位发表评论。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>普京打击乌克兰粮食出口的举措会产生什么连锁反应？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>俄罗斯表示，拒绝续签该协议，要求西方国家根据去年与联合国签署的另一项协议的条款，采取更多措施促进俄罗斯食品和化肥出口。俄罗斯长期以来一直声称西方制裁损害了本国的农业产业，尽管今年的出口预计将创下历史新高。去年，俄罗斯黑海舰队克里米亚总部遭到无人机袭击，俄罗斯曾短暂退出该协议，并指责乌克兰是此次袭击的罪魁祸首。</p><p>分析人士和外交官表示，在埃尔多安采取一系列举措后，俄罗斯取消了该协议，这标志着他的外交政策出现了新的倾斜，远离俄罗斯并转向西方。埃尔多安决定将去年根据囚犯交换条款居住在土耳其的一群乌克兰军事指挥官送回乌克兰，并表示他批准瑞典加入北大西洋公约组织，这激怒了俄罗斯。</p><p> “我认为普京不像以前那样信任埃尔多安，”曾在土耳其驻莫斯科大使馆任职的前高级外交官古尔鲁·盖泽尔说。 “我认为俄罗斯方面，特别是克里姆林宫正在质疑埃尔多安的思维方式。他不接电话的情况并不常见，”她谈到普京时说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=CC71B144-B6D5-4ADE-B69C-819DC994B692&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fgreat-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">周二早些时候，俄罗斯在退出确保乌克兰出口产品安全通过黑海的协议后数小时对敖德萨发动了导弹袭击。 《华尔街日报》的马修·卢克斯摩尔从港口城市报​​道。照片：Igor Tkachenko/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>土耳其前外交官、伊斯坦布尔智囊团 Edam 主任西南·乌尔根 (Sinan Ulgen) 表示，土耳其向西方倾斜可能有助于陷入困境的土耳其经济，而且埃尔多安可能会认为，瓦格纳准军事组织最近在俄罗斯发动叛乱后，普京的力量被削弱了。</p><p>他补充说：“我们现在正处于土俄关系的不同阶段，埃尔多安不再需要普京，而普京更需要埃尔多安。”</p><p>莫斯科退出该协议也给俄罗斯与中国这个克里姆林宫最有影响力的国际伙伴的关系带来压力。流经黑海倡议的粮食约有四分之一流向中国。</p><p>美国智库战略与国际研究中心食品和水安全专家凯特琳·威尔士表示：“中国公开表示，它非常希望看到黑海倡议继续下去。”</p><p> Last Thursday, Ukraine&#39;s deputy economy minister met with a senior Chinese official in Beijing, where the sides talked about expanding their grain exports. On Sunday, China told the UN&#39;s Security Council that given the initiative&#39;s importance in global food security it should be implemented, while state-run media has carried stories saying the initiative should continue.</p><p> Russia has said that it will replace any lost Ukrainian grain on global markets. But while it has the reserves of wheat to do that it won&#39;t be able to replace the huge amounts of Ukrainian corn that goes to China, Welsh said. Ukraine typically accounts for more than a quarter of all Chinese corn imports and a large slice of barley purchases, according to the Ukrainian Grain Association.</p><p> Russian attacks on Ukrainian Black Sea ports this week hit and partly destroyed 60,000 metric tons of grain that were set to be loaded onto a ship headed to China, according to Kernel, the Ukrainian grain traders who sold the cargo.</p><p> Around half of Ukrainian grain, or some 29 million metric tons, was exported through the Black Sea corridor during the last harvest season, of 2022 to 2023, according to the Ukrainian Grain Association. The rest was evenly split between Ukraine&#39;s Danube ports, where grain is loaded onto barges and sent to Romanian ports, and by land across its borders with the European Union.</p><p> It will be hard for Ukraine to replace grain exports that went directly to China through Black Sea ports because the countries they will now be exported through, mainly Poland and Romania, don&#39;t have the same approvals from China, whether on hygiene or otherwise, as Kyiv does, according to Sergey Ivashchenko, a director at the Ukrainian Grain Association.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Chao Deng and Oksana Pyrozhok contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Jared Malsin at <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a> and Alistair MacDonald at <a href="mailto:Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 10:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinAlistair MacDonald]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> ukraine</category><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>Tayyip Erdogan</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Taiwan Amps Up Chinese-Invasion Drills to Deliver a Message: War Could Happen]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>政府力图与公众的自满情绪作斗争，军事和民用演习规模更大、声音更大、协调性更好<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092728"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=660B6D5E-1625-4388-9BA2-82874CFBAE59&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftaiwan-amps-up-chinese-invasion-drills-to-deliver-a-message-war-could-happen-705e6343&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">在乌克兰战争和对中国大陆入侵的担忧日益加剧之后，台湾的年度军事演习和民用演习今年急剧扩大。 《华尔街日报》访问了这个民主岛屿，了解它准备如何保卫自己。照片：王乔宇<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092728"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joyu-wang" itemprop="url" rel="author">王乔宇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 5:54（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-amps-up-chinese-invasion-drills-to-deliver-a-message-war-could-happen-705e6343"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>台湾台南——俯瞰台湾海峡的这座城市的郊区，两栋住宅楼前爆炸，一栋摇摇欲坠地靠在另一栋上。消防队员冲向闷烧的残骸，扑灭大火，并开始疯狂搜寻幸存者。</p><p>附近的扩音器里响起一个女声，向围观的人群讲述这一场景。</p><p> “中国人的袭击导致一辆公共汽车翻倒，几栋建筑物倾斜倒塌，许多人被困，”该女子说。 “台南市遭受不分青红皂白的导弹袭击。”</p><p>这一场景和其他模拟混乱场景均以电影制作价值呈现，是周二在台湾南部城市进行的灾难应对演习的一部分，该演习与针对假想的中国入侵的多日军事演习同时进行。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="570" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825566?width=860&amp;height=570" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周四，台湾一个主要港口附近举行了反登陆演习。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Joyu Wang/华尔街日报</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>演习和演习<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-concerns-about-taiwan-put-focus-on-islands-defensive-weakness-11619113253?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">每年都会举行</a>，并且总是带有戏剧性的元素，但今年的规模更大、声音更大、更加协调。与会者和政治分析人士表示，此举的目的是传达一个明确的信息：战争随时可能爆发。</p><p>台湾总统蔡英文过去一直对这种情绪持谨慎态度，担心播下可能削弱经济的恐慌情绪。但随着中国在台湾周边的军事活动加剧，以及乌克兰战争凸显了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-invasion-ukraine-battle-of-kyiv-ragtag-army-11663683336?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">做好充分准备的民众</a>的重要性，台北的算计已经开始发生转变。</p><p>北京的共产党领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-taiwan-relations-tensions-explained-11653322751?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">认为台湾是中国的一部分</a>，并誓言要把这个自治岛屿置于自己的控制之下，必要时可以使用武力，尽管他们从未统治过台湾。中国领导人习近平将解决台湾问题视为其所谓的民族复兴中国梦的核心，并表示这是一项“不应该代代相传的任务”。</p><p>没有迹象表明军事对抗迫在眉睫，但近年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-threatens-retaliation-if-kevin-mccarthy-meets-taiwans-tsai-ing-wen-66e5e597?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，随着台北和华盛顿之间的关系日益紧张，将台湾与</a>中国分隔开的 100 英里宽的台湾海峡的紧张局势加剧。一些军事分析家警告说，数十年来一直生活在理论上的中国入侵威胁下的台湾民众并没有充分意识到冲突风险的增加。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="464" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825567?width=700&amp;height=464" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">模拟中国导弹袭击住宅楼的爆炸是周二在台湾台南市进行的灾难应对演习的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Joyu Wang/华尔街日报</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>台南的防灾演习通常以台风、地震等自然灾害为重点。今年，市政府官员首次将演习时间与年度军事和空袭演习同时进行，并练习应对战时情况。</p><p>在政府高级官员和高级军事官员与美国驻台北大使馆的一支特遣队一起观看的情况下，该市模拟了对建筑物的导弹袭击，火焰云射向天空，一枚肮脏的炸弹在民用机场爆炸。</p><p>警察队伍的任务是制服冒充居民并试图制造混乱的中国渗透者，而社区领导人则练习疏散居民和学童。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “今天在台南举行的演习，包括模拟战时情景，不仅仅是因为俄罗斯乌克兰战争引发了国际敏感性的提高，”台湾行政院院长陈建仁周二在演习后表示。 “这更反映出中国对我国不断的威胁和挑衅。”</p><p>蔡英文在新冠病毒检测呈阳性后错过了周二的演习，但她周四驾驶悍马车出现在台湾西北海岸的海滩上，观看一场异常大型的反登陆演习，并参观了一条军事战壕，她说这个战壕的灵感来自于乌克兰的堑壕战。 。</p><p> “未来，我们面临的威胁和挑战将更加复杂。我们需要预测复合威胁场景，制定相关预案，加强训练演练。”她周四表示。</p><p>台湾淡江大学中国军事专家林英宇表示，反登陆演习在现代战争中的军事意义较小，但有助于传递一个象征性信息，即台湾有能力抵御中国军队。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824742?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台湾总统蔡英文周四视察军事演习。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ANN WANG/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>林说，“天助自助者”，这是台湾国防部试图向华盛顿领导人传达的信息，在与北京的任何军事对抗中，台北都需要华盛顿领导人的支持。 “我们不是一块容易被踢碎的豆腐。”</p><p>美国军事规划者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-military-readiness-china-threat-us-defense-11635174187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">质疑台湾军队是否已做好</a>与中国大陆对抗的准备，理由是准备不足且士气低落。蔡政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-to-extend-mandatory-military-service-11672129529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">扩大了征兵规模并全面改革了训练</a>，以解决这些问题。</p><p>这是自去年夏天时任众议院议长<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">南希·佩洛西</a>访问台北后，中国以军舰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-boasts-of-ability-to-blockade-taiwan-as-military-exercises-continue-11659695158?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">模拟军事封锁</a>包围台湾以来的首次演习和演习。当时，一些西方政治分析人士猜测，北京的愤怒反应可能会让普通台湾民众意识到中国所构成的日益严重的威胁。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>未来五年台湾发生战争的可能性有多大？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>几个月后，效果似乎减弱了。国立政治大学选举研究中心3月份进行的一项调查显示，超过30%的受访者将中国入侵的可能性评为6或更高（从0到10），其中10代表入侵的确定性。这一比例略高于一年前的 28%。</p><p>由于预计周五将袭击该岛东南海岸的强台风，本周的几次演习不得不改变或取消，但演习规模的扩大和强度的增加至少给一些人留下了印象。</p><p>在台北的一次防空演习中，送货司机吴景荣不得不将摩托车停在地铁站地下30分钟。他说，他理解由于台湾海峡紧张局势加剧，有必要让公民做好应对紧急情况的准备。<br><br> “作为平民，我们能做的就是找到合适的地方藏身，”他说。 “剩下的就看政府了。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824743?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台湾桃园国际机场的士兵本周参加模拟中国入侵的演习。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布伦南·奥康纳/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年的军事演习，正式名称为“汉光演习”，比以往更加关注对主要基础设施和交通枢纽（包括岛上最大机场）的威胁。</p><p>周三，前台湾特种部队士兵廖欧文与一位前军人朋友前往天文台，观看部队从四架黑鹰直升机上降落，模拟袭击台湾桃园国际机场。他驳回了有关机场首次参加演习导致航班延误的投诉。</p><p> “如果台湾不努力自力更生，没有人愿意帮助你，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Joyu Wang： <a href="mailto:joyu.wang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joyu.wang@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 09:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-amps-up-chinese-invasion-drills-to-deliver-a-message-war-could-happen-705e6343</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-amps-up-chinese-invasion-drills-to-deliver-a-message-war-could-happen-705e6343<author><![CDATA[Joyu Wang]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[$2 Billion Default Followed Warnings to Everyone but Investors]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Beneficient executives and board directors headed for the exits over signs of trouble—long before a financial blowup that is now under investigation by the SEC and which could leave nearly 28,000 investors empty-handed <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825361/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photos: Reuters, Getty Images, Bloomberg News, EagleView, Kansas Reflector <span>Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photos: Reuters, Getty Images, Bloomberg News, EagleView, Kansas Reflector</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087085"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087085"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alexander-gladstone" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alexander Gladstone</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 5:29 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Brad Heppner had the grand idea of bringing investment opportunities enjoyed by Wall Street institutions to small-fry investors. It brought misery instead.</p><p> The Texas-based financial entrepreneur named his company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/an-asset-management-merger-ended-in-bankruptcy-while-its-architect-got-174-million-11659103557?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beneficient</a> , a branding mashup of beneficial and beneficent, the quality of doing good. To bankroll his new venture, Heppner and his business partners merged it with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-investors-face-1-3-billion-hit-after-asset-managers-detour-into-startups-11656066601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">GWG Holdings</a> , an established financial-services firm that sold bonds to retail investors. GWG would raise the money. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-firm-beneficient-pushed-boundaries-before-bond-programs-collapse-11671757459?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beneficient</a> would put it to work. Heppner served as board chairman of both companies and recruited a cast of notable directors, including two former <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ecGmw61nR6I" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Federal Reserve Bank presidents</a> and legendary Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach.</p><p> From all appearances, Heppner and his team had a promising strategy: Beneficient would use money from GWG&#39;s investor base to acquire stakes in private-equity funds and other highflying assets, giving rank-and-file investors access to markets typically off limits to them. The first funds from GWG to Beneficient, $50 million, landed in June 2019. As far as board directors were concerned, Beneficient would use the money to expand the business, former directors said.</p><p> Instead, it kicked off what became one of the biggest financial blowups to strike retail investors in years.</p><p> Within weeks, Tiffany Kice, Beneficient&#39;s chief financial officer, discovered that millions of dollars went to payments for Heppner&#39;s nearly 1,500-acre east Texas ranch and his personal travel via private jet. Kice, formerly an audit partner at KPMG and CFO of Chuck E. Cheese, also found that the company had been using a faulty accounting method that would misstate revenue, according to private documents viewed by The Wall Street Journal.</p><p> What Kice learned about Beneficient&#39;s inner workings didn&#39;t, in her view, square with the best interests of investors, according to people who worked with her at the time. She repeatedly pressed Heppner for answers, and after one contentious exchange in July 2019, Kice shared a stack of financial documents with Sheldon “ Shelly” Stein, a senior board director, according to confidential court papers that allege what happened. Heppner&#39;s angry reaction had rattled her. She told Stein that she was afraid of him, the court papers show. Kice left the documents with Stein and resigned days later.</p><p> Over the next months, Kice&#39;s exit was followed by the departures of three board directors, including Stein, as well as a parade of C-suite executives—chief compliance officer, chief technology officer, operations chief and general counsel. The exits were largely driven by fears that the business risked catastrophic losses to investors while potentially benefiting Heppner, said former board directors and executives. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824325?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Brad Heppner, left, the founder and chief executive officer of Beneficient.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tim Carpenter/Kansas Reflector</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Even after the wave of resignations, some of the remaining board directors promoted Beneficient in TV interviews and at investment conferences, helping sell GWG bonds through a nationwide network of broker-dealers. One high-profile director, former Dallas Fed President Richard Fisher, appeared in promotional videos, describing Beneficient&#39;s aim to become “an important contributor to the US economy.”</p><p> Last year, GWG defaulted on $2 billion in debt and filed for chapter 11, leaving retail investors with potential losses of as much as $1.3 billion. In separate bankruptcy and federal class-action lawsuits, investors accused board directors—including Fisher, former Atlanta Fed President Dennis Lockhart, private-equity mogul Tom Hicks and insurance executive Bruce Schnitzer</p> —of facilitating a Ponzi scheme orchestrated by Heppner. Fisher, Lockhart, Hicks and Schnitzer denied any wrongdoing in court papers and declined to comment. Heppner denied wrongdoing in court papers and through a spokesman.<p></p><p> The Securities and Exchange Commission has been investigating GWG and Beneficient since 2020, regarding Beneficient&#39;s accounting methods and payments to Heppner-related entities, according to company disclosures and people familiar with the matter. The SEC in a June 29 letter to Beneficient warned of possible civil enforcement action that would allege securities violations. Heppner, the company&#39;s founder and chief executive, received a similar letter, a company filing shows. Beneficient and Heppner said their actions were appropriate, according to the filing.</p><p> “I have always worked to maintain best-in-class governance and transparency, consistent with my fiduciary duties as a director,” Heppner said in a statement to the Journal last year. “I always relied on the counsel of independent advisers and attorneys when in the boardroom.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1980" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/eb288cd8-8e1a-4393-94c7-336a96c5ba3b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> A Beneficient spokesman said that costs for Heppner&#39;s private jet travel and ranch were effectively paid for by a reduction in preferred equity held by Heppner-related entities. These and other related-party transactions were legal and properly disclosed, the spokesman said. He noted that Kice signed Beneficient&#39;s audit statement on June 14, 2019. Kice didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Warnings about GWG and Beneficient began in summer 2019 and spread among executives and board directors through the fall and into 2020, long before GWG&#39;s collapse. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> The only group who didn&#39;t have a clue were nearly 28,000 mom-and-pop investors, including many retirees. This account is based on securities filings, court documents, emails and interviews with former executives, former board directors and people familiar with the matter.</p><h3> Board revolt</h3><p> Heppner, 57 years old, grew up in a Mennonite community in rural Kansas and attended Southern Methodist University in Dallas. He won a scholarship established by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="company-name">Goldman Sachs</a> partner Charles Harmon Jr. , who became his mentor. Harmon later lent Heppner $1 million for one of Heppner&#39;s first deals, an $18 million buyout of asset-management firm Crossroads Group.</p><p> After Harmon died in 1997, his widow established a financial trust for Heppner with $5,000. Heppner put Crossroads and other financial ventures into the trust, which he referred to as the Harmon trust. In 2003, Heppner sold Crossroads and his other companies to Lehman Brothers for roughly $200 million. Most of the proceeds remained in the Harmon trust, and Heppner used some of the money to start Beneficient—a loan of roughly $140 million that was made through an affiliated trust. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824502?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An aerial view from 2021 of Brad Heppner&#39;s Bradley Oaks Ranch in Bradford, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: EagleView</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In addition to Kice&#39;s warnings, Stein had by August 2019 also heard from other Beneficient executives who aired concerns about Heppner&#39;s leadership, including general counsel Jessica Magee, a former SEC enforcement lawyer, and operations chief Philip Eckian, according to emails from around that time. Magee declined to comment. Eckian didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Stein, then-president of liquor distributor Southern Glazer&#39;s, began to scrutinize Beneficient&#39;s financial documents. He teamed up with two other directors— David Glaser,</p> a former senior executive at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, and Bruce Zimmerman, now chief investment officer of billionaire Ray Dalio&#39;s family office, said people familiar with the matter.<p></p><p> They looked closely at payments made to business entities related to Heppner. Stein asked board director Tom Hicks about $9 million in such payments. Hicks said he believed the payments were proper, according to an email to Stein viewed by the Journal.</p><p> Zimmerman told others on the board in an August 2019 email that he was troubled by the payments to Heppner-related parties. Stein agreed. “Cash flow is a major problem and it is unacceptable to make payments from GWG to BEN to related parties,” he wrote in response. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825362?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A photo taken during a Beneficient event at Bradley Oaks Ranch. Brad Heppner is seated on left, wearing glasses.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Heppner urged payment on the loan from the Harmon trust affiliate that had funded Beneficient, emphasizing that it was a contractual obligation. “Those trusts are fed up and want to be paid out,” Heppner said in a July 15, 2019, email to Hicks that was forwarded to Stein. “We need to be very careful on this, because they have been accommodating. That said they aren&#39;t going to be so willing anymore.”</p><p> Most of the board directors didn&#39;t realize at the time that Heppner had a substantial financial interest in the Harmon trust and its affiliates, former directors said. Heppner is a beneficiary of the trusts, which lend money to Heppner&#39;s other business ventures, according to a recent securities filing.</p><p> Heppner pressed ahead with fundraising efforts. In a Sept. 7, 2019, email to directors, he said bond sales for August had grown to nearly $50 million. “GWG doesn&#39;t want to get ahead of itself,” he wrote, “but if GWG continues to see similar levels of interest in September, I hope to be updating you about a new all-time monthly high in sales very soon.”</p><p> He noted in the email that Staubach, the former Cowboys quarterback, was scheduled to give the keynote address at an Oct. 15, 2019 finance conference in Las Vegas. “Going forward we will continue to lean on you, our directors, to be ambassadors for Ben and GWG&#39;s revamped bond program,” he wrote. Staubach declined to comment.</p><p> Board directors Glaser, Zimmerman and Stein became increasingly skeptical that Beneficient&#39;s strategy of acquiring stakes in private-equity funds from individuals would generate enough revenue to repay GWG bond investors. Fisher and Zimmerman asked Heppner for the company&#39;s financial projections in a Sept. 21, 2019, email. Heppner provided forecasts showing annual revenue was expected to grow from near zero to at least $1.7 billion by 2025.</p><p> Matters came to a head at an Oct. 10, 2019, meeting at Beneficient&#39;s headquarters in Dallas. Zimmerman, Glaser and Stein weren&#39;t persuaded that there was a basis for the bullish projections during tense discussions with Heppner, Hicks and Schnitzer. Zimmerman resigned and left the room. Glaser and Stein quit the board within days.</p><p> Two other directors, former CNBC anchor Michelle Caruso-Cabrera and Staubach, resigned months later. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/678ef8fc-4ee5-4cb5-b891-d30f942dd92c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> &#39;Violation of trust&#39;</h3><p> Bond sales continued to climb through 2020. In October that year, the SEC notified GWG, the parent company of Beneficient, that it was under investigation. The federal agency requested details about Beneficient&#39;s accounting and valuation practices, as well as its transactions with related parties.</p><p> In July 2021, the SEC concluded that the accounting method Beneficient had been using was incorrect: the firm had been making loans to its own subsidiaries and counting the interest it received as revenue. That was a problem Kice had noted. Bond sales were halted until the companies corrected their financial statements.</p><p> GWG didn&#39;t disclose the extent of losses in Beneficient&#39;s private-equity investments until the companies restated their financial statements in November 2021, according to securities filings. That also was the first time they disclosed the SEC probe.</p><p> By then, GWG was on the verge of collapse. When the company tried to relaunch its bond-selling program, the SEC warned the company&#39;s broker-dealers that they, too, would be investigated if they continued to sell the bonds. Around that time, Beneficient separated as an independent company. With bond sales frozen, GWG failed to pay interest payments due in January 2022 and filed for chapter 11 that April.</p><p> In the years since linking up with Beneficient, GWG sold $1.3 billion in bonds, with much of the proceeds used to repay GWG&#39;s past investors. Beneficient received $230 million from GWG and paid at least $174 million to entities associated with Heppner. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825081?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Clifford Day, a retiree in Boca Raton, Fla.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Grace Day</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Clifford Day, a 74-year-old retired social worker in Boca Raton, Fla., said that following the GWG-Beneficient merger he had invested around $220,000, a significant portion of his life savings, into GWG bonds on the recommendation of his financial adviser. “This violation of trust has shaken me to my core,” he said after GWG defaulted.</p><p> Day&#39;s broker, David Arlein, said he had been impressed by the presence of board directors such as Fisher, the former Dallas Fed president, and Staubach, who led the Cowboys to two Super Bowl victories.</p><p> Fisher, Lockhart, Hicks and Schnitzer, who remained as Beneficient directors after at least five colleagues resigned, have each received more than $1.7 million in compensation for their years of service, according to securities filings.</p><p> The bankruptcy court formed two trusts to try to return some of the $1.3 billion owed to GWG bond investors. One trust will aim to sell the roughly 170 million shares of Beneficient that GWG owns. The other trust is weighing litigation against Beneficient and its current and former directors.</p><p> Last month, Beneficient went public in a merger with a special-purpose acquisition company. The company said in securities filings and marketing materials that the transaction would value it at $3.5 billion. Beneficient ended up raising around $8 million through the SPAC deal. Its stock closed at $2.14 on Thursday, down more than 85% from its opening price on June 8.</p><p> On July 17, the company announced the launch of an online platform to encourage investors in private-equity funds to swap their assets for Beneficient stock.</p><p> Write to Alexander Gladstone at <a href="mailto:alexander.gladstone@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alexander.gladstone@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 09:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873<author><![CDATA[Alexander Gladstone]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> leder</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>保险</category><category>Financial Investment Services</category><category> Security Brokering/Dealing</category><category> Diversified Holding Companies</category><category> Business/Consumer Services</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Bankruptcy</category><category> Corporate Funding</category><category> Ownership Changes</category><category> Corporate Actions</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Corporate Financial Difficulty</category><category> Private Equity/Venture Funding</category><category> Securities Regulations</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Financial Crime</category><category> Fraud</category><category>证券欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>有益的</category><category>BENF</category><category> GWG Holdings</category><category> GWGHQ</category><category> Brad Heppner</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>bankruptcy</category><category>企业融资</category><category>ownership changes</category><category> corporate actions</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>corporate financial difficulty</category><category> private equity</category><category>风险投资</category><category>securities regulations</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>securities fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>保险</category><category>financial investment services</category><category> security brokering</category><category>交易</category><category>diversified holding companies</category><category>商业</category><category>consumer services</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel’s Government Looks at Next Steps in Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在通过限制法院权力的法律后，联盟现在正在寻求改变法官的任命方式<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092879"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825179?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">系着蓝色领带的以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡表示，他将给反对派在 11 月中旬之前达成妥协方案的时间。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：abir sultan/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092879"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日凌晨 4:34 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联盟<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周取得了重大胜利</a>，通过了旨在重建该国司法机构的一揽子立法的第一部分。现在，它已准备好迎接更多。</p><p>最重要的是让民选官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-judge-at-the-heart-of-israels-constitutional-crisis-de698670?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">控制法官遴选委员会</a>，这是司法改革中最具争议的部分之一。内塔尼亚胡在三月份搁置了一项法案，该法案将让政府在面对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-israels-citizen-soldiers-forced-netanyahu-to-retreat-on-judicial-overhaul-21d55e4e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大规模抗议和预备役军人威胁的情况</a>下获得该委员会的多数控制权，如果该法案获得通过，则将停止报到。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-faces-fresh-stand-off-with-israeli-reservists-over-judicial-overhaul-b974d3f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来自预备役军人的抗议和威胁</a>并没有阻止内塔尼亚胡推进该计划的第一部分，该计划于周一在没有反对派支持的情况下通过成为法律。内塔尼亚胡周四在接受美国广播公司新闻采访时表示，如果反对派不与政府妥协，他准备继续单方面通过司法改革。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡说：“现在他们看到我们已经准备好在没有他们的情况下采取行动——我们拥有多数——也许我们能够与他们一起采取行动。”他表示，他将给予反对派在 11 月中旬之前达成妥协方案的时间。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>在两轮谈判失败后，以色列反对派领导人亚伊尔·拉皮德表示，他将拒绝参加不认真的谈判。 “反对派不会参与一场空洞的谈判，”他周一表示。</p><p>近30周以来，以色列人一直在抗议一项旨在限制最高法院权力并将更多控制权交给立法者的司法改革计划。周四晚上， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9?mod=world_lead_pos4&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数万人走上街头抗议</a>政府重塑司法机构的努力。</p><p>该计划的支持者表示，为了控制自由派、激进的法院，这些改变是必要的，因为法院太容易推翻民选官员的意愿。反对者表示，该计划破坏了制衡制度，并将允许内塔尼亚胡的右翼、极端民族主义和宗教保守党派联盟通过法院通常认为违宪的立法。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825237?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特拉维夫抗议司法改革的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825232?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫游行反对拟议的改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>以色列议会 (Knesset) 将于 7 月 30 日进入夏季休会期，直到 10 月中旬才会返回，这意味着在任何立法重新进行辩论之前都将有一个暂停。</p><p>领导司法改革的议员之一西姆查·罗斯曼(Simcha Rothman)表示，该联盟希望继续改变法官的任命方式，并“以负责任的方式继续纠正司法系统”。他说他希望在与反对派合作的同时做到这一点。</p><p>司法任命委员会由九名成员组成，目前由现任法官、以色列律师协会成员、执政联盟代表以及传统上反对派成员组成。投票是分开的，因此没有一个团体在委员会中拥有多数发言权。</p><p>目前还没有提出新的法案，内塔尼亚胡和罗斯曼表示，他们将在未来几周内考虑如何修改立法。</p><p>但该法案的一个版本于二月份在议会提出，但于三月份被搁置， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">该版本将改变司法遴选委员会</a>，以便执政联盟将被允许在不受反对的情况下任命其任期内的前两名最高法院法官。此后，最高法院的任命将需要一名反对派成员和一名法官的支持。最高法院院长也将由该委员会任命，而不是按照目前的资历任命，而且委员会中将不再有律师协会成员。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上个月在接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示</a>，他认为赋予立法者在委员会中的决定性发言权没有问题。</p><p> “目前持续存在的批评是，你不能让民选官员选择法官，因为那是民主的终结。那么，在这种情况下，美国就不是一个民主国家，”内塔尼亚胡说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825211?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">反对党领袖亚伊尔·拉皮德表示，他将拒绝参加不认真的谈判。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：AMMAR AWAD/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>总部位于耶路撒冷的智库以色列民主研究所的法律学者阿米尔·福克斯表示，现行的法官任命制度是为了让法官和政客都拥有否决权。他说，有保守派法官正在排队加入该委员会。</p><p> “我认为这个系统提供了一个非常好的和多元化的最高法院，并且随着时间的推移它会变得更加平等，”他说。</p><p>以色列司法部长亚里夫·莱文（Yariv Levin）是政府计划的设计者之一，他拒绝召开委员会来任命法官，直到他能够改变委员会目前的组成。</p><p>最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">定于 9 月听取以拉皮德为首的中间派 Yesh Atid 党的请愿书</a>，要求召开委员会来填补法院的空缺职位。一些法律学者表示，最近投票通过，任命两名新议员加入该委员会，其中一名来自反对派，一名来自联盟，因此该委员会无法进行变更。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>除了改变法官的任命方式外，该联盟还希望推行其他立法。这包括使总检察长和部长法律顾问的意见成为咨询性的意见，而不是像目前那样具有约束力。该联盟还希望阻止最高法院废除以色列的准宪法法律（即基本法），并限制法院可以审理的案件。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡告诉《华尔街日报》，他不会寻求一项允许以色列议会以简单多数议员推翻最高法院裁决的法案。此后，他的联盟中的一些人表示，内塔尼亚胡告诉他们，他将以不同的形式收回该法案。</p><p>科赫莱特论坛 (Kohelet Forum) 是一家帮助制定政府立法的耶路撒冷智库，其政治学家亚伯拉罕·迪斯金 (Abraham Diskin) 表示，自 20 世纪 70 年代末以来掌权的右翼政府从未能够完全实现其愿景，因为最高法院一再否决主要的立法优先事项。</p><p> “事实上，所有问题的真正决定权都不在他们手中，”他说。 “法院是政策和决策中所有因素中唯一且最强大的。”</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 08:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Benjamin Netanyahu</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[5 Ways That Buying a Car Has Drastically Changed]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Car sellers and car buyers confronted a whole host of challenges in the pandemic, and now it&#39;s clear that some of the challenges are here to stay. &#39;Normal is not our benchmark anymore.&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824241/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="A customer examines the inside of a Tesla Model X at the opening of a new  Tesla dealership in New Mexico.越来越多的汽车公司采用了特斯拉所推广的直接面向消费者的销售模式。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A customer examines the inside of a Tesla Model X at the opening of a new Tesla dealership in New Mexico. More car companies have adopted the direct-to-consumer sales model popularized by Tesla. Albuquerque Journal/Zuma Press <span>Albuquerque Journal/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086503"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086503"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-felton" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ryan Felton</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/5-ways-buying-car-changed-pandemic-643cb2c0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Factory shutdowns. Crippling parts shortages. Near-empty dealership lots.</p><p> The US auto industry has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/a-guide-to-the-current-crazy-car-market-823a1ecf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">been through a lot</a> these last three years, forcing car executives, car dealers and car buyers to adjust on the fly and find new ways of doing business. Now it looks like many of those changes are here to stay.</p><p> The upheaval began in the early days of the Covid pandemic, when car companies <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/detroit-car-makers-target-may-18-u-s-restart-date-11588026203?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">halted work at their factories</a> and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-chip-crisis-hits-auto-makers-hard-11635411518?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">global supply chain froze up</a> , preventing carmakers from getting many of the parts they needed. A global semiconductor shortage has constrained the supply of chips needed for core components, further limiting production.</p><p> But demand for new cars bounced back much quicker than anyone expected.突然之间，美国人想要汽车，而经销店大部分都被清空了。 The result: Buyers were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dealers-and-buyers-are-both-worried-cars-are-too-expensive-11675476870?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">willing to pay record sums for those vehicles that were available</a> , fueling a stretch of highly profitable years for both car companies and auto retailers.</p><p> Within the past year, the supply-chain disruptions have begun to ease and stock levels at new-car dealerships are rising. Still, car companies don&#39;t want to return to the days of jam-packed lots and deep discounts, and many car buyers would now prefer to simply order their car online instead of haggling with a dealer.</p><p> “Will we ever get back to normal?”汽车研究公司 Edmunds 的分析师杰西卡·考德威尔 (Jessica Caldwell) 说道。 “I don&#39;t think so, because normal is not our benchmark anymore.”</p><p> Here are five ways that buying a car may have permanently changed.</p><h3> 1. Slim pickings</h3><p> American car dealerships have historically stocked their lots with rows and rows of cars, giving buyers the option of picking one and driving off the lot that day.</p><p> It is a model of convenience that also has its downsides. Having too many cars that don&#39;t sell can trigger <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dealers-dangle-deals-to-move-outgoing-models-11565874003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a wave of discounts</a> that can weigh on automaker profits.</p><p> The pandemic-era car shortages showed the car business a different path.</p><p> Dealers were stuck with vast stretches of bare asphalt.汽车服务公司考克斯汽车 (Cox Automotive) 的数据显示，待售或在途车辆数量从疫情爆发前的超过 300 万辆降至 2021 年 9 月约 854,000 辆的历史最低水平。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="882" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824290?width=1260&amp;height=882" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A car dealership lot in Gurnee, Ill., in 2021. Some automakers have said they plan to keep the availability of cars and trucks on dealership lots permanently constrained in the years ahead.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: tannen maury/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> And yet, buyers were still shelling out for new wheels, splurging on whatever they could get their hands on.</p><p> The rising popularity of</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">Tesla</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> direct-to-consumer sales model, in which shoppers largely order their vehicles online, also got car-company executives to start <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fords-talk-of-new-ev-selling-rules-rattles-some-dealers-11656504003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">rethinking whether it makes sense to keep so many vehicles in stock</a> .<p></p><p> Some automakers, including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="company-name">Ford Motor</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GM" class="">General Motors</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> have said they plan to keep the availability of cars and trucks on dealership lots permanently constrained in the years ahead, an effort aimed at sustaining their run of strong profits. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825146?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In June, there were about 1.9 million new cars and trucks in transit or available at dealerships, a sign that availability was improving. But many in the car business don&#39;t anticipate it will return to prepandemic levels—at least not in the short term.</p><p> “We&#39;re not going to go back to the high inventories that we had in the past,” said Ford&#39;s Chief Financial Officer</p> John Lawler last year.<p></p><p> On car lots, this could mean shoppers have fewer colors, options and trim levels readily available to choose from.更有可能的是，汽车零售商将提供最受欢迎的配置，但数量较少。</p><p> Want something slightly different?您可能必须直接从工厂订购，然后等待其构建和交付。 Turnaround times vary by model, but can often take a few months—or in some cases, much longer.</p><p> Rory Harvey, GM&#39;s president of North America, said car buyers have gotten comfortable with planning a lease or purchase a few months ahead and waiting for their vehicle to arrive.</p><p> “Customers&#39; buying behavior has changed,” he told the Journal last week.</p><h3> 2. Stubbornly high prices</h3><p> If you&#39;re looking to buy a new car in the coming years, be prepared to splurge.</p><p> Before the pandemic, American buyers were already gravitating to pricier trucks and SUVs, pushing average selling prices higher. This shift led some car companies like GM and Ford to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/america-has-fallen-out-of-love-with-the-sedan-1535169698?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">kill off many of their cheaper</a> , small-car and sedan models, giving buyers fewer affordable options. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825480?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The pandemic-era shortages only supercharged the inflation.从2019年底到去年年底，新车的平均售价上涨了36%以上。 In mid-2021, nearly two-thirds of new cars were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/car-dealers-are-selling-more-vehicles-above-the-sticker-price-11624959180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">selling at prices above the manufacturer&#39;s suggested sticker</a> —an unprecedented situation that left many buyers shocked and frustrated.</p><p> Car companies have long leaned on rebates, cash bonuses and other promotions to motivate buyers. But during the pandemic, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/car-leasing-plummeted-during-pandemic-could-take-years-to-recover-11674875959?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">those kinds of discounts mostly evaporated</a> . Even now, bargains are still hard to come by.</p><p> The average selling price hit a record $47,362 in December of last year, according to industry-research firm JD Power, a figure that has since fallen to roughly $46,000 in June. Today, there are only four car models that have a sub-$20,000 sticker price, compared with 18 a decade ago, according to Edmunds. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="851" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824293?width=1260&amp;height=851" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A new Chevrolet truck is displayed in a dealership in Glendale, Calif.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mario Tama/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The higher costs are straining buyers&#39; budgets. The average monthly payment for a new-car loan hit $733 in this year&#39;s second quarter, compared with $562 in 2019, according to Edmunds. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824181?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> On electric vehicles, in particular, where automakers have been expanding rapidly, prices have dropped 20% from June 2022 to last month, according to Cox Automotive. The decline has been mostly driven by a series of price reductions by EV leader Tesla and Ford.</p><p> Still, buyers shouldn&#39;t expect more big breaks in the near term.</p><p> “We&#39;re not necessarily expecting prices to rise the way they have in the past couple years,” said David Oakley, an analyst at GlobalData, an industry-research firm. “It&#39;s more that we don&#39;t see them coming back down.”</p><h3> 3. Lower industrywide sales</h3><p> As a result of the first two factors, carmakers are preparing for a future where they simply sell fewer new cars than they once did.</p><p> Before the pandemic, US auto-industry sales were booming, posting several straight years where the annual tally was at or near 17 million. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824183?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> This historic run was abruptly halted by the health crisis. Sales fell to 14.5 million in 2020, and then last year, dropped again to 13.7 million, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/auto-industry-expected-to-post-worst-u-s-sales-year-in-more-than-decade-11672808763?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the lowest recorded figure since 2011</a> .</p><p> The decline was largely driven by prolonged parts shortages, particularly on computer chips that are used in everything from multimedia displays to heated seats.</p><p> Carmakers gave priority to whatever parts they could obtain to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jeep-dodge-maker-posts-strong-results-amid-higher-demand-and-prices-11627983391?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">build the most expensive models</a> , which helped fatten profits.</p><p> The models that were available were often the priciest ones, stretching many buyers&#39; pocketbooks.许多购物者完全退出了新车市场。</p><p> This year, sales have picked up again as factory output has stabilized and dealers are finally restocking their lots. Analysts project they could hit about 15 million in 2023.</p><p> Still, rising interest rates and persistently high sticker prices are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dealers-and-buyers-are-both-worried-cars-are-too-expensive-11675476870?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">keeping many buyers away from new-car showrooms</a> . It could be years—even next decade—before US auto sales approach the 17 million mark again, according to GlobalData.</p><p> The lower selling pace could have broader repercussions across the industry, heightening pressure on automakers to scale back factory output and trim assembly-line jobs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824294?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Vehicles for sale at a Chrysler dealership in Richmond, Calif.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Jeep-owner <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/STLA" class="company-name">Stellantis</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stellantis-to-stop-work-at-factory-in-illinois-11670615448?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">already idled one factory</a> indefinitely last December and its chief executive, Carlos Tavares, has warned additional shutdowns could be forthcoming.</p><p> “If the market shrinks, we don&#39;t need so many plants,” Tavares said in January.</p><h3> 4. Fewer lease deals</h3><p> For many Americans, leasing has long been a go-to for getting into a new car at a more affordable monthly payment than taking out an auto loan.</p><p> In the years leading up to the pandemic, about one-third of all vehicles sold were leased. And car companies, hoping to make the deals more attractive, threw money at the promotions, even if they make more money selling cars outright. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825421?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> But with inventory tight, many automakers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/car-buyers-shun-leases-as-deals-and-vehicles-dwindle-11648154831?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">drastically cut back on these lease deals</a> , and the ones they were offering were far more expensive.</p><p> In many cases, it became more economical to finance a vehicle than lease it—a complete reversal of years past.</p><p> The share of leased vehicles nosedived as a result, hitting about 16% in the second half of last year, the lowest level since the 2008-2009 financial crisis, according to industry-research firm JD Power.</p><p> While some lease deals are returning—particularly on EVs that can take advantage of a federal tax credit—analysts expect it to take <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/car-leasing-plummeted-during-pandemic-could-take-years-to-recover-11674875959?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the better part of this decade for the auto-leasing market to fully rebound</a> .</p><p> For one, car companies don&#39;t need as many leases, since they can sell nearly everything they make without the need for lease deals or other promotions.</p><p> And the drop-off in leasing has also effectively reduced the number of customers turning cars back into dealerships. That means there are fewer Americans looking to renew their lease deals.</p><p> With higher interest rates, leasing is going to remain expensive for both automakers and consumers.除非制造商开始改善条款，否则它不太可能迅速卷土重来。</p><h3> 5. More expensive used cars</h3><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824295?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Used cars for sale at a dealership in Chicago, Ill. With fewer people buying new cars, supplies on used ones are expected to remain tight.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯科特·奥尔森/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Buyers hoping to find a better deal on the used-car lot could be in for a surprise.</p><p> Prices for preowned vehicles skyrocketed during the pandemic, climbing at a steeper rate than on the new-car side, in part because they are not tethered to a manufacturer&#39;s suggested retail price.</p><p> Many consumers, unable to find what they wanted at a new-car dealership, flocked <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/looking-to-buy-a-used-car-expect-high-prices-few-options-11620639000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to the used-car market looking for a better selection</a> and more affordable price tags. The shift, in turn, created another supply crunch—one that was as severe. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824176?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> On top of that, many owners were <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-average-age-of-vehicles-on-u-s-roadways-hits-a-record-12-2-years-11653303602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">holding on to their cars longer</a> , worried about finding a replacement, which slowed the number of cars coming into the used market. The drop-off in leasing only made the problem worse, because fewer of those vehicles were filling the preowned pipeline.</p><p> The average price paid for a used vehicle hit nearly $30,000 at the end of 2021 and has continued to remain at elevated levels, according to industry data.</p><p> At one point, used-car values were rising so fast many owners saw a surprising reversal: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-car-in-your-garage-may-be-gaining-value-11644575402?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">their once-depreciating assets were actually rising in value</a> .</p><p> As a result, the number of buyers purchasing used cars has also tapered off. Cox Automotive 的数据显示，去年二手车销量约为 3620 万辆，比疫情爆发前下降了约 10%。</p><p> Within the past year, used-car prices have begun to moderate but they still remain volatile, subject to sudden increases and declines. That&#39;s because they are highly dependent on how fast inventory bounces back on the new-car side.</p><p> And without more people coming in to buy new cars, supplies on used ones will remain tight, keeping prices high, dealers say.</p><p> “If we&#39;re not getting the cars on trade-in, we have to go out and buy them,” said Geoffrey Pohanka, chairman of Maryland-based dealer Pohanka Automotive Group. “Certainly, this sends a ripple effect.”</p><p> Write to Ryan Felton at <a href="mailto:ryan.felton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.felton@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B5EE9B2E-0DF8-4707-99C6-5BA4E825A7A3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2F5-ways-buying-car-changed-pandemic-643cb2c0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Converting gas cars into electric vehicles is becoming more common, with several companies offering ways to “upcycle” classic cars and fleet vehicles. WSJ&#39;s George Downs explores why retrofitting isn&#39;t more widespread. Illustration: George Downs<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/5-ways-buying-car-changed-pandemic-643cb2c0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/5-ways-buying-car-changed-pandemic-643cb2c0<author><![CDATA[Ryan Felton]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>wsjexchange</category><category> Motor Vehicles</category><category> Passenger Cars</category><category>零售批发</category><category>Motor Vehicle Dealing</category><category> New Car Dealing</category><category> Specialty Retailing</category><category>汽车</category><category>零售</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Cars</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>cars</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>motor vehicles</category><category> passenger cars</category><category>零售</category><category>wholesale</category><category> motor vehicle dealing</category><category> new car dealing</category><category> specialty retailing</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Replaced, Then Erased: Mystery Deepens Around China’s Former Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nearly all mentions of Qin Gang as minister scrubbed from Foreign Ministry website, intensifying speculation <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Freplaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Beijing reappointed top diplomat Wang Yi to replace Qin Gang as foreign minister during an emergency session on Tuesday, without addressing Qin&#39;s mysterious absence. Chinese leader Xi Jinping had handpicked Qin seven months earlier. Photo: Florence Lo/Pool Reuters/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Wenxin Fan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 27, 2023 9:52 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HONG KONG—China&#39;s former foreign minister, who was replaced on Tuesday after he went missing from public view for more than a month, is now disappearing from parts of the Foreign Ministry&#39;s website—an erasure that is intensifying intrigue around what happened to him.</p><p> Authorities didn&#39;t provide a reason for their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=world_lead_pos5&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">decision to remove</a> Qin Gang from his post, which has now been filled—at least temporarily—by his predecessor Wang Yi. The Foreign Ministry previously cited <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">unspecified health reasons</a> for Qin&#39;s absence.</p><p> Since replacing him with Wang, the ministry has scrubbed nearly all mentions of Qin as the foreign minister from its official website. Many references to Qin in his most recent role likewise disappeared from the ministry&#39;s account on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="">Weibo</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> a popular social-media platform.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>在毛泽东时代，众所周知，共产党会从照片和其他官方记录中删除高级官员，通常是在他们失宠并被清洗之后。此后的几十年里，这种高水平的擦除非常罕见，而且可能从未如此引人注目地进行过。</p><p> The changes attracted attention on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="company-name">Weibo</a> and in other corners of the Chinese internet, fueling fevered speculation about Qin&#39;s fate.</p><p> “Had Qin Gang not ever been a foreign minister?” one Chinese lawyer wrote in a post on Weibo. “The way the website handled this isn&#39;t appropriate.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823935?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">五月份在北京上映的《秦刚》已经从公众视野中消失一个多月了。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>The 57-year-old served less than seven months as Chinese leader Xi Jinping&#39;s handpicked foreign minister following <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an unusually rapid rise</a> through the foreign-service ranks. Qin&#39;s online erasure undermined the notion that he was replaced as a result of serious health issues, political analysts said.</p><p> “Even if health issues had necessitated Qin&#39;s removal as foreign minister, there is no reason this would lead to the deletion of the past record of his meetings within the MFA site,” wrote David Bandurski, director of the China Media Project, a <a href="https://chinamediaproject.org/2023/07/26/chinas-foreign-minister-is-removed-and-erased/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">US-based research group</a> .</p><p> Asked about the changes at a regular press briefing on Wednesday, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Mao Ning said the website was being updated according to protocols.</p><p> Bombarded by questions from reporters about Qin&#39;s status at the briefing, Mao said she had no new information to provide.外交部网站上发布的新闻发布会记录中，所有记者提出的有关秦和毛泽东回应的问题都被省略了。</p><p>围绕秦的戏剧性事件发生在北京和华盛顿的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-china-see-fragile-opportunity-to-repair-ties-8ad7ddff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">微妙时刻</a>，因为两国最近在紧张局势加剧之际才重新建立了高层沟通。 Political analysts say the 69-year-old Wang, the Communist Party&#39;s top foreign-affairs specialist, was likely installed as an interim replacement to buy time for Xi and other senior officials to find a more permanent solution.</p><p> US Secretary of State Antony Blinken,</p> on a visit to the Pacific island nation of Tonga, said he wished Qin well and promised to work with Wang, whom he has met on several occasions.<p></p><p> “I&#39;ve also known Wang Yi for more than a decade,” Blinken said. “I anticipate being able to work well with him, as we have in the past.”</p><p> Political analysts said Qin&#39;s replacement was unlikely to derail diplomacy between the US and China in the long run because Xi sets foreign policy, though it serves to highlight the increasing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">opacity of China&#39;s political system</a> .</p><p> Searches on the Foreign Ministry website for Qin&#39;s name in Chinese or English returned no results on Wednesday. Qin continued to be listed as foreign minister in one statement on the site, which described him as representing China in the establishment of diplomatic ties in Honduras in March. Unlike the hundreds of other statements that have been removed, his name didn&#39;t appear in the headline on the Honduras item. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824129?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6 月 18 日，国务卿安东尼·布林肯在北京会见了时任外交部长秦刚，几天前他最后一次公开露面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：利亚·米利斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Searches for Qin&#39;s name through the ministry&#39;s official accounts on the popular app</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">WeChat</a> still produced results from his time as foreign minister. News items describing Qin in his previous roles as vice minister and ambassador to the US remain on the ministry&#39;s website.<p></p><p> State media accounts of Qin&#39;s removal haven&#39;t mentioned any change to his role as a state councilor, a senior government ranking in China&#39;s cabinet. As of Wednesday afternoon, the cabinet&#39;s website had been updated to remove mention of his ministerial role but continued to list his other titles, including as a member of the Communist Party&#39;s elite Central Committee.</p><p> China&#39;s internet censors have taken a selective approach to Qin. On Wednesday, Weibo was hiding search results under some hashtags related to his removal, as well as under a hashtag for “The Search for Qin,” a fantasy TV series set in China&#39;s ancient Qin dynasty.</p><p> But users otherwise were given space to continue indulging in speculation about the reasons for his disappearance, including the possibility of an extramarital affair.</p><p> “This is certainly not a normal job transfer,” wrote one Weibo user, nodding to the seeming ubiquity of the affair rumor on Chinese social media. The post received more than 10,000 likes.</p><p> Write to Wenxin Fan at <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bf4d14ac-311a-4b61-9cc1-ce0772d8de02.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 01:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Weibo</category><category>世界银行</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item></channel></rss>